06630nam a22008895i 9780812298123DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122981237 a10.9783/97808122981232doi  a(DE-B1597)577468  a(OCoLC)1273975217  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC328.6 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a303.6223/eng00aReverberations :bViolence Across Time and Space /ced. by Zerrin Özlem Biner, Yael Navaro, Alice von Bieberstein, Seda Altuğ. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. SPACES OF DEATH -- tChapter 1. Chronicling Deaths Foretold -- tChapter 2. Speculating on Death -- tChapter 3. Culture of Dispossession in the Late Ottoman Empire and Early Turkish Republic -- tPART II. VIOLENCE AND THE SUPER NATURAL -- tChapter 4. Violence and Spirituality -- tChapter 5. Icons of Uncaring -- tChapter 6. Digging -- tChapter 7. Maskun -- tPART III. VIOLENCE AGAINST NATURE AND INFRASTRUCTURAL VIOLENCE -- tChapter 8. Infrastructural Violence in Jerusalem -- tChapter 9. Tenses of Violence -- tChapter 10. The Wounded Landscape -- tChapter 11. Architectural Witnessing at the Former Madımak Hotel in Sivas, Turkey -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe turn to the nonhuman in the humanities and social sciences has arguably been mobilized through a washing away of political violence, its histories, and its traces. Reverberations aims to redress this problem by methodologically and conceptually placing political violence and nonhuman entities side by side. The volume generates a new framework for the study of political violence and its protracted aftermath by attending, through innovative ethnographic and historical studies, to its distribution, extension, and endurance across time, space, materialities, and otherworldly dimensions, as well as its embodiment in subjectivities, discourses, and imaginations. Collectively, in the study of political violence, the contributions focus on human agencies and experiences in engagement with nonhuman entities such as objects, land, fields, houses, buildings, treasures, trees, spirits, saints, and prophets. In a variety of contexts, the scholars herein ask the crucial question: What can be learned about political violence by analyzing it in the terrain of relationality between human beings and nonhuman entities? How are things such as objects, spaces, natural phenomena, or spiritual beings entwined in histories of political violence? And vice versa—how are histories of political violence implicated in nonhuman things?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical violencevCase studies. 0aPolitical violencexEnvironmental aspects. 0aPolitical violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aPolitical Science.1 aAltuğ, Seda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltuğ, Seda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaumann, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBieberstein, Alice von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBieberstein, Alice von, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBiner, Zerrin Özlem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiner, Zerrin Özlem, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDawdy, Shannon Lee, 